        contentMd: "# Exam High Yield\n\n| Topic | High-Yield Fact |\n|-------|-----------------|\n| Femoral triangle boundaries | Inguinal ligament (superior), Sartorius (lateral), Adductor longus (medial) |\n| Contents lateral to medial | **NAVEL**: Nerve, Artery, Vein, Empty space, Lymphatics |\n| Femoral nerve root value | **L2, L3, L4** (largest branch of lumbar plexus) |\n| Femoral artery is continuation of | **External iliac artery** |\n| Mid-inguinal point | Midway between **ASIS and pubic symphysis** |\n| Largest branch of femoral artery | **Profunda femoris** |\n| Femoral nerve position to sheath | **Outside** the femoral sheath |\n| Femoral canal boundary (medial) | **Lacunar ligament** |\n| Femoral hernia more common in | **Females** |\n| Longest muscle in body | **Sartorius** |\n| Only biarticular quadriceps | **Rectus femoris** |\n| Patella type | Largest **sesamoid bone** |\n| Knee jerk reflex | **L3, L4** (femoral nerve) |\n| Adductor canal roof | **Sartorius** |\n| Adductor canal ends at | **Adductor hiatus** in adductor magnus |\n| Great saphenous vein drains into | **Femoral vein** at saphenous opening |\n\n## One-Liners\n- Femoral pulse is felt at the **mid-inguinal point**\n- Femoral hernia passes through the **femoral canal**\n- The femoral ring is bounded medially by the **lacunar ligament**\n- The saphenous nerve is the **longest purely sensory nerve** in the body\n- Vastus medialis obliquus (VMO) prevents **lateral subluxation of patella**",
