        contentMd: "# Exam High Yield\n\n| Topic | High-Yield Fact |\n|-------|-----------------|\n| Obturator nerve root value | **L2, L3, L4** (from lumbar plexus) |\n| Obturator nerve enters thigh via | **Obturator foramen** |\n| Key landmark for obturator nerve divisions | **Adductor brevis** (anterior division in front, posterior behind) |\n| Largest adductor muscle | **Adductor magnus** |\n| Adductor magnus nerve supply | **Dual**: Obturator (adductor part) + Tibial/sciatic (hamstring part) |\n| Adductor hiatus transmits | **Femoral artery** (becomes popliteal artery) |\n| Only adductor crossing knee | **Gracilis** |\n| Pes anserinus muscles | **SGS**: Sartorius, Gracilis, Semitendinosus |\n| Pectineus nerve supply | Mainly **femoral nerve** |\n| Howship-Romberg sign | **Obturator hernia** (pain on medial thigh) |\n| Corona mortis | **Abnormal obturator artery** from inferior epigastric |\n| Obturator neurectomy indication | **Cerebral palsy** (adductor spasm, scissoring gait) |\n| Hip pain referred to knee via | **Obturator nerve** (L2,3,4) |\n| Most commonly strained adductor | **Adductor longus** |\n\n## One-Liners\n- Obturator nerve is compressed in **obturator hernia** causing Howship-Romberg sign\n- Gracilis is the most **superficial muscle** of the medial compartment\n- Adductor magnus has **4 osseoaponeurotic openings** for perforating arteries\n- Abnormal obturator artery is present in **30%** of individuals",
